**who —** ATARI LYNX — an exereunesis sphere — the teardown

**what —** The Lynx was the first colour, backlit handheld — and the most powerful of its day — with custom chips that scaled and rotated sprites in hardware, years ahead of rivals. It was also a battery-devouring brick that the cheaper, frugal Game Boy buried commercially.

**where —** the teardown — a made machine, opened and explored  Framework inputs: the chips; the buses; the spec; the lore  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)

**why —** The Lynx was the first colour, backlit handheld — and the most powerful of its day — with custom chips that scaled and rotated sprites in hardware, years ahead of rivals. It was also a battery-devouring brick that the cheaper, frugal Game Boy buried commercially.

**how —** Rendered from the public technical record.

**◌ the mythos —** The Lynx was the first colour, backlit handheld — and the most powerful of its day — with custom chips that scaled and rotated sprites in hardware, years ahead of rivals. It was also a battery-devouring brick that the cheaper, frugal Game Boy buried commercially. the inside of a made machine, laid bare

